Putin the guilty party
MOSCOW – Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden agreed that Alexei Navalny was a victim of Novichok nerve agent. Navalny is Russia’s top opposition figure and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Luckily, since Navalny survived, relations between Russia and Germany have not deteriorated further.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Angela Merkel announced that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for his freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious and can only and must be responded to by the Russian government.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation shows that the Russian government was behind the incident, the EU Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless, poisoning is prohibited under the rules of the World Convention on Chemical Weapons.
This is not the first time that the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political enemies.
In 2018, Russian former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin denies both incidents strongly.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov insisted there was "no evidence whatsoever to blame the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service chief Sergei Naryshkin even said it was the work of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to damage the reputation of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly misplaced, but he does point out a fact: the Navalny case has more downsides for Russia than upsides.
Poisoning a prominent political opponent just before a major election, and using a toxin developed during the Soviet era, makes little sense.
Especially so at a time when Belarusian citizens are protesting the August elections.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial response to the Navalny case was particularly puzzling.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government that carried out the act, then this murder would be a failed operation.
Putin has been a Darth Vader (the lead antagonist in Star Wars) in international politics, interfering in US elections, inciting street protests in France, encouraging Brexit, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, farsighted, and cunning.
Why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why was Navalny able to flee to Germany and be quickly confirmed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, with the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline to Germany under threat of cancellation.
This murder clearly wasn't worth it.
In fact, it has only further fueled public opposition to the Russian authorities' actions.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, blaming Western intelligence agencies is even more unreasonable.
If such charges were true, German and Swedish scientists would not have spoken about the Novichok nerve agent.
More likely, it was a conspiracy planned by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to be silent before the election, or perhaps it was due to his anti-corruption investigations.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political henchmen, while loyal, are very foolish, and they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, knowing only a few of them the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts shared similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza was the coordinator of the Pro Khodorkovsky Public Council.
The poisoning of Peter Verchelov, the publisher of the independent news website MediaZona, in 2018.
MediaZona reports on abuses of power within the Russian judiciary.
Going further back to 2006, the poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko, a former KGB officer who frequently criticized Russia's security services.
As with the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane en route from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived; two years later, she was shot dead in an elevator in her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death did immense damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an attempt to exonerate the Kremlin.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered the crime, he created a system that made such atrocities possible. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death was what the Kremlin wanted, and making their master Putin happy is the ultimate goal of his henchmen.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning fails, they will not be punished.
Because they do it for the president's benefit.
Those who want to find evidence of the poisoning may be disappointed.
Either way, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must clearly state that they will take sanctions against Russia even if it affects their own economy.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities in Russia fall on him.
